WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.920
 Hello, and welcome to another walkthrough for Django for Everybody.

00:00:04.920 --> 00:00:09.020
 Today what we're going to talk about is the autograder.

00:00:09.020 --> 00:00:14.460
 So you just finished your assignment and you are looking at needing to earn a grade.

00:00:14.460 --> 00:00:20.740
 So you have drchuckanywhere.com after the install of the first assignment and it's working and

00:00:20.740 --> 00:00:23.420
 you've got a URL and away it goes.

00:00:23.420 --> 00:00:27.520
 And now you launch from your learning management system to earn a grade and you're presented

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:28.800
 with this page.

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:31.780
 This is an autograder page.

00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:35.900
 So you notice it has the instructions for that assignment that you just completed, right?

00:00:35.900 --> 00:00:39.460
 So you go to the autograder, it usually tells you where the instructions are.

00:00:39.460 --> 00:00:42.880
 And so there's rules in those instructions and we went through these in a completely

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:47.200
 separate video and you got to follow those and sometimes there's little details down

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:51.420
 here about characters you're supposed to do or ways you're supposed to do things.

00:00:51.420 --> 00:00:56.820
 That gets checked for, but then the autograder has its own set of rules and so it puts these

00:00:56.820 --> 00:00:59.460
 codes in various places.

00:00:59.460 --> 00:01:04.540
 That's one of the ways the autograder tracks whether or not stuff is moved between students

00:01:04.540 --> 00:01:10.860
 and so that you're grading your version of this, not someone else's application, okay?

00:01:10.860 --> 00:01:16.220
 So let me show you a little bit about what happens right when you're going to press this

00:01:16.220 --> 00:01:18.140
 evaluate button.

00:01:18.140 --> 00:01:21.540
 So this is a couple of slides I have on how the autograder works.

00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:22.580
 So what is it?

00:01:22.580 --> 00:01:27.700
 So the autograder is a piece of software that I wrote on www.dj4e.com, it's launched from

00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:33.380
 Canvas or Coursera, that is going to grade your assignment, check to make sure it's okay,

00:01:33.380 --> 00:01:35.640
 and it's a very simple program.

00:01:35.640 --> 00:01:40.060
 If you took Python for everybody, you wrote a program that does web crawling.

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:45.660
 So what this is is just a smart web crawler that decides if your page meets a certain

00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:47.740
 set of specifications and then gives it a grade.

00:01:47.740 --> 00:01:52.620
 So it sends requests the web page and it checks the response to make sure that it's right,

00:01:52.620 --> 00:01:54.620
 then continues to the next page.

00:01:54.620 --> 00:01:59.580
 And if it makes it all the way through all of the tests, then a correct grade is sent

00:01:59.580 --> 00:02:00.860
 back to Canvas.

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:02.780
 So I have an philosophy and approach.

00:02:02.780 --> 00:02:04.580
 I'm trying to make these simple.

00:02:04.580 --> 00:02:06.700
 Sometimes there's autograders that try to trick you.

00:02:06.700 --> 00:02:08.740
 I want to keep it as simple as possible.

00:02:08.740 --> 00:02:11.740
 I want to just check to see did you follow the instructions, right?

00:02:11.740 --> 00:02:15.020
 And you'll make lots of little mistakes and this autograder is going to catch them.

00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:16.500
 I give you a lot of feedback.

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:19.420
 I try not to make the autograder mysterious.

00:02:19.420 --> 00:02:23.140
 Although you will think I'm doing that, it is not true.

00:02:23.140 --> 00:02:25.460
 All it does is did you check the instructions?

00:02:25.460 --> 00:02:29.700
 It's doing the simplest thing it can possibly can, which is not always super simple.

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:32.940
 So there's no guarantee that the AI-generated code that looks good in the browser is going

00:02:32.940 --> 00:02:34.700
 to pass the autograder.

00:02:34.700 --> 00:02:39.940
 And so you can't come and say, look, it has a button and it says the word hello world.

00:02:39.940 --> 00:02:43.740
 Well, it might be that it's the wrong kind of button or you're using an anchor tag or

00:02:43.740 --> 00:02:48.820
 a button tag because AI just did it, because AI can build code an infinite number of ways.

00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:52.100
 If you follow my instructions, you tend to build it one way.

00:02:52.100 --> 00:02:54.900
 And that's what the autograder is looking for.

00:02:54.900 --> 00:02:57.820
 Did you follow the instructions?

00:02:57.820 --> 00:03:01.100
 Following instructions, doing your own work, and then the autograder is going to take you

00:03:01.100 --> 00:03:04.820
 to the bugs, give you a grade when you fix those bugs, and it should be straightforward.

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:08.640
 I'm not saying you can't use AI on the way.

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:12.580
 So here's kind of a block diagram of how this process works.

00:03:12.580 --> 00:03:17.420
 So you're developing, say, your website on drchuckpythonanywhere.com, you're using a

00:03:17.420 --> 00:03:21.580
 browser and you're clicking on it and you're hitting refresh and you're getting errors

00:03:21.580 --> 00:03:24.420
 and you're fixing the errors and reloading your application.

00:03:24.420 --> 00:03:30.060
 So that top process of just developing and testing is really important.

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:34.140
 And some of the autograders or assignments will give you manual testing.

00:03:34.140 --> 00:03:38.260
 And I think it's really important for you to manually test first.

00:03:38.260 --> 00:03:41.660
 And then hopefully when it all works and you've manually tested it, then it's time to send

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:43.420
 it to the autograder.

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:50.680
 And so you go in from your learning management system, launches into djangoforeverybody.com

00:03:50.680 --> 00:03:55.160
 with an LTI token, and then you press the evaluate button.

00:03:55.160 --> 00:04:01.820
 And then what happens is djfree.com makes its own connections to your website and it

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:06.140
 sends requests and it receives HTML back and it reads that HTML.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:11.220
 And based on what that HTML is, it either says, whoops, I got the wrong thing, or it

00:04:11.220 --> 00:04:16.780
 goes on and then eventually, using Learning Tools Interoperability, it sends a grade back

00:04:16.780 --> 00:04:19.620
 to Canvas or Coursera.

00:04:19.620 --> 00:04:24.140
 And the first autograder that we're gonna show here really just does one, but you can

00:04:24.140 --> 00:04:30.380
 get toward the end and djfree.com will make up to 50 request response cycles.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:34.540
 And it's got a lot of debug output and so you're gonna have to scroll down.

00:04:34.540 --> 00:04:38.300
 I'll probably make another video in the second half so you can see some of the techniques

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:42.080
 when the autograder gets a lot more sophisticated.

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:48.660
 So now before, last thing to do before we go to the autograder demonstration is to basically

00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:50.160
 say what does it look like.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:52.860
 So it's written in a programming language called PHP.

00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:55.460
 It's all up in GitHub.

00:04:55.460 --> 00:04:57.460
 It's all open source.

00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:02.580
 If you really wanna get smart or if you wanna train your AI bot, you can look at the autograder

00:05:02.580 --> 00:05:05.800
 code and AI would understand this.

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:10.700
 And so you might say I'm doing this homework, I'm submitting it to this autograder and it's

00:05:10.700 --> 00:05:11.820
 not working.

00:05:11.820 --> 00:05:13.060
 Help me fix my code.

00:05:13.060 --> 00:05:16.140
 That is not a good strategy, but it's okay.

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:18.500
 So you look here, it's got a couple lines of code.

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:24.900
 So it's got some URL, probably a URL that you pass in, and then it makes a connection.

00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:30.460
 This code uses a library that emulates a browser with things like cookies and get requests

00:05:30.460 --> 00:05:35.040
 and put repost requests and responses, et cetera.

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:37.340
 And this is kind of just basic crawler.

00:05:37.340 --> 00:05:41.100
 And then I get the HTML back and I search for the string hello.

00:05:41.100 --> 00:05:45.260
 And then in the next line, I'm checking to see if you've got the code that I wanted you

00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:49.100
 to put in correctly and it finds it and then you got your grade.

00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:51.840
 Otherwise it says I didn't find it, no score sent.

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:56.540
 So this autograder is very, very simple.

00:05:56.540 --> 00:06:01.680
 That's pretty much the core code if this autograder is like 12 lines of code.

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:02.680
 It's an easy one.

00:06:02.680 --> 00:06:04.060
 So you wanna read this stuff closely.

